    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. It's like having a pair of magical, invisible gloves that always match. If you put on one glove, the other glove will automatically appear in the matching color and size, even if it's on the other side of the world. This is different from classical correlation, where objects are just influenced by their surroundings and don't have this instant, mysterious connection. In classical correlation, it's like having two separate, ordinary gloves that don't magically match. Quantum entanglement is like a secret handshake between particles that only they understand, and it's a bit like a secret language that only they can speak. It's a bit like having a pair of enchanted goblins who always know what the other is up to, even if they're separated by a vast distance.",
      "source": "target",
